th + 1)) // 2\n                start = end\n        \n        # Calculate the number of subarrays for the last increasing sequence\n        length = len(nums) - start\n        total_count += (length * (length + 1)) // 2\n        \n        return total_count\n```\n\nThis solution iterates through the list `nums` and keeps track of the start of each strictly increasing subarray. When it finds a non-increasing pair, it calculates the number of subarrays in the previous increasing sequence and adds it to the total count. Finally, it calculates the number of subarrays for the last increasing sequence after the loop. The formula `(length * (length + 1)) // 2` is used to calculate the number of subarrays in a sequence of length `length`.", "estimated_date": 1661644800000}